ROCm decode: try mlock/MADV_HUGEPAGE on 80 GiB model map to cut page-fault sys time

Status: PROPOSED. Discovered via the HIP graph capture experiment (now-retired tsk-34): a 200-token decode run shows 13.7s system CPU and 244k minor page faults. At ~30us per minor fault that is ~7s of sys time, which roughly matches the launch-overhead-eliminated theoretical residual.

Hypothesis: the sys time is driven by demand-faulting pages of the model map (or HIP runtime allocations) into the working set. If we mlock the model map up-front, or madvise it with MADV_HUGEPAGE, we should see minor faults drop sharply and sys CPU shrink with it. Whether wall improves depends on whether faulting was on the critical path or amortized into background sys time.

Approach:
1. Find where the model map is created in ds4.c / ds4_rocm.c (set_model_map / set_model_map_range path).
2. Add mlock(map, size) call after map is fully populated. Likely needs  or CAP_IPC_LOCK; fall back to madvise(MADV_WILLNEED | MADV_HUGEPAGE) if mlock fails.
3. Measure /usr/bin/time -v before/after: minor faults, sys, wall.
4. If model map cannot be safely mlocked (size limits), try madvise alone.

Validation:
- ./ds4_rocm_kernel_test (40 tests) still OK.
- Coherent decode on the standard prompt (-n 200 --temp 0 --seed 42).
- Compare wall, sys CPU, decode t/s vs current baseline (15.35 t/s, sys 13.7s, wall 33.4s, 244k minor faults).

Why this is promising: the sys-CPU number puts an upper bound on what *any* host-side optimization can recover. After page faults drop, the next dominant sys-CPU consumer becomes visible.